\cf0 The dietary contributions of aquatic and terrestrial sources to T.extensa\'92s diet and niche width varied across treatments, primarily attributed to differences in prey availability (hypothesis II) resulting from the effects of ALAN and Crayfish treatments. The increased proportion of aquatic insects in T. extensa\'92s diet under ALAN and crayfish treatments suggests these factors may enhance aquatic insect emergence or availability. Meanwhile, reduced proportion of terrestrial insects may reflect lower availability or reduced attraction to light. Web placement on vegetation near or overhanging the streams may have facilitated the greater capture of emerging aquatic insects by Tetragnatha extensa.  For instance \
