\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The moderate overlap in 95% prediction ellipses between each treatment and the control (ranging from 38% to 41%) suggests that 
\f2\i \strokec2 T. extensa
\f1\i0 \strokec2  maintained partial dietary consistency across treatment conditions. However, the reduced overlap also indicates a shift in isotopic niche under ALAN, crayfish, and ALAN + Crayfish treatments, likely reflecting changes in prey availability or foraging dynamics driven by these stressors. For instance\
\
The broader isotopic niche widths observed under ALAN (0.87\'89\'b2) and ALAN + Crayfish (1.04\'89\'b2) treatments suggest increased prey availability or dietary diversity for 
\f2\i \strokec2 T. extensa
\f1\i0 \strokec2  under artificial light conditions. This may be due to ALAN attracting a wider range of insects, thereby increasing their availability and likelihood of capture in the spiders' webs (REF). These findings support the idea that ALAN may promote trophic generalization in 
\f2\i \strokec2 T. extensa
\f1\i0 \strokec2  by altering insect community composition or behavior, leading to broader isotopic niches (REF). For instance
