\f1 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The slight increase in the proportion of aquatic insects in the spider diet under the crayfish treatment compared to the ALAN treatment suggests differing foraging behavior of 
\f2\i Tetragnatha
\f1\i0  spiders under each condition. Although aquatic insect emergence, primarily dominated by Chironomidae, was reduced in the crayfish treatment, the spiders consumed a slightly higher proportion of aquatic insects in this condition. This may be due to the positive phototactic response of Chironomidae, which could have directed their flight toward light sources, reducing the likelihood of being caught in spider webs under ALAN. Previous studies have shown that 
\f2\i Tetragnatha
\f1\i0  and other riparian spiders are generally attracted to lit areas due to increased prey availability. However, this aggregation may lead to intraspecific competition, thereby reducing the proportion of aquatic insects in individual spider diets.Moreover, the combined effect of both crayfish and ALAN resulted in a 9% and 6% reduction in aquatic insect proportions compared to the crayfish-only and ALAN-only treatments, respectively. This suggests that the combined impact of both stressors is greater than their individual effects. \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 The lower proportion of terrestrial insects observed across treatments may be influenced by the horizontal web placement of 
\f2\i \strokec2 Tetragnatha
\f1\i0 \strokec2  on vegetation near or overhanging the water, which may limit access to terrestrial prey. Additionally, the behavioral traits of terrestrial insects could play a role. For example, Cicadellidae are known to be negatively phototactic and exhibit limited flight activity, while Curculionidae are predominantly ground-dwelling and rarely enter the vertical space where spider webs are typically located. These traits may reduce the likelihood of terrestrial insects being intercepted by 
\f2\i \strokec2 Tetragnatha
\f1\i0 \strokec2  webs under both treatment conditions.
